g.text: Radioprotection by medicinal aromatic plants
Review
Executive summary
The enhanced adverse effect of synthetic drugs and antibiotics has paved way toward the utilization of natural
products of plant origin unambiguously in recent years.
The present review explored the protection against cellular damage resulting from radiation of approximately
thirty aromatic plant extracts or plant-derived compounds.

It is a well-known fact that radiation is a powerful cytotoxic agent. Reactive oxygen species such as superoxide
anion, singlet oxygen, hydroxyl radical, nitric oxide, hydrogen peroxide and peroxyl radicals generated by
ionizing radiation in biologic system causes cellular injury due to lesions in DNA and proteins.
The radical scavenging and antioxidant properties such as reduction in radiation-induced lipid peroxidation are
some of the notable characteristics of aromatic plant extracts studied in various models of radiation damage.
